Adjust rack to top position and heat broiler to high. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, core, and thinly slice @long green pepper{1} crosswise into strips.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{3%tablespoon} with @hot sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste. Stir in water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large, preferably ovenproof, pan over medium-high heat. Add green pepper; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until softened and lightly blistered, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add another drizzle of oil and @diced chicken thighs{10%ounce} to pan with green pepper. Season with @southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon}, salt, and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. TIP: If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Stir in one-quarter of the @green salsa{7.06%ounce} (you'll use the rest in the next step); taste and season with salt and pepper.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #medium bowl{}. Wipe out pan.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water; pat dry with paper towels. Open package of chicken and drain off any excess liquid. Swap in shrimp or chicken for beef; cook, stirring occasionally (no need to break up into pieces!), until opaque and cooked through, 4-6 minutes.

Place a small amount of beef filling on one half of each @flour tortillas{6}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas. Place seam sides down in pan used to cook filling. TIP: For 4 servings or if pan isn't ovenproof, place enchiladas in a #9-by-13-inch baking dish{}.

Top with remaining salsa and sprinkle with @mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Broil enchiladas until browned and bubbly, ~{3-4%minutes}. TIP: Watch carefully to avoid burning.

Drizzle with crema and serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.